Los retos de las bibliotecas en la era de internet
En <a href="http://nathan.torkington.com/blog/2011/11/23/libraries-where-it-all-went-wrong/">Libraries: Where It All Went Wrong</a> hay una conferencia que dió Nat Torkington a un grupo de bibliotecarios australianos y asiácticos.

Entresaco algunas notas:

Las compara con Microsoft: hubo un momento en que tenían un papel crítico, pero el monopolio despareció.

<blockquote>
I'm telling you this because libraries are like Microsoft.

At one point you had a critical role: you were one of the few places to conduct research. When academics and the public needed to do research into the documentary record, they'd come to you. As you now know, that monopoly has been broken.
</blockquote>

No debemos fiarnos sólo de tener un papel importante en el mundo, porque puede que los demás no lo vean/reconozcan:

<blockquote>
The Internet, led by Google, is the start and end of most people's research. It's good enough to meet their needs, which is great news for the casual researcher but bad news for you.

Now they don't think of you at all.

Oh yes, I know all the reasons why the web and Google are no replacement for a healthy research library. I know the critical importance of documentary heritage. But it's not me you're talking to at budget time.  It's the public, through the politicians.
</blockquote>

Hay que digitalizar, hay que estar en internet, hay que estar en la web, pero no de cualquir manera. Hay que hacerlo bien:

<blockquote>
But then if I look at the results of those digitization projects, I find the shittiest websites on the planet.  It's like a gallery spent all its money buying art and then just stuck the paintings in supermarket bags and leaned them against the wall.
</blockquote>

Estar mal es peor que no estar.

Cinco formas en las que los bits no funcionan como los átomos:

- Los bits son fáciles de copiar
- El acceso es obligatorio
- Internet es más grande que tú
- Los bits son tan baratos que tenemos muchos
- Internet conecta cosas

Dicho de otra forma:

<blockquote>
- be useful as well as important
- collections, discovery, distribution
- bits are cheap to copy
- access is expected
- the Internet is bigger than you are
- we have too many bits
- the Internet connects things
</blockquote>


No puedes permitirte hacerlo mal en digital:

<blockquote>
You can't afford to be bad at digital. I tell businesspeople: It's your inventory, it's your storefront, it's your customer service line, it's your supply chain, it's your advertising, it's your profit and loss.  
</blockquote>

El éxito consiste en convertirse en relevante para la gente: hacer cosas que otros utilicen, aprovechar los conocimientos de tus empleados y valorar los servicios que proporcionan.

En definitiva, nada muy nuevo, ni muy diferente de lo que se podría esperar. Pero parece que mucha gente no lo entiende y estarán condenados a la irrelevancia y a desaparecer.

